Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high. Bring 3 cups water and
@veggie stock concentrate{1} to a simmer in a #medium pot{} over medium-low
heat. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Halve, peel, and mince
@shallot{1}. Finely chop @jalapeño{1}, removing ribs and seeds if you prefer
less heat.

Place @red bell pepper{1} under broiler. Broil, turning occasionally, until
skin is blackened all over.

> TIP: Alternatively, hold bell pepper with metal tongs over open flame of a
> gas stove, turning to blacken.

Place in a #large bowl{} and cover with plastic wrap. Set aside to steam for
at least ~{15%minutes}.

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add
garlic, shallot, and jalapeño. Cook, tossing, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.
Stir in @cumin{1%teaspoon}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add @Arborio rice{3/4%cup} to pan. Cook, stirring, until grains are translucent,
~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce heat to medium-low. Add stock ½ cup at a time, stirring
after each addition. Allow rice to absorb most of stock before adding more.
Continue until grains are al dente and creamy, ~{25-30%minutes}. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

While rice cooks, drain half the @corn{1/2%can} from can.

> We sent more than needed - only use half the can.

Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4}. When bell pepper is done steaming, peel and
discard blackened skin. Halve, core, and remove seeds, then slice into thin
strips.

Once risotto is done cooking, stir in bell pepper, corn, @Monterey jack cheese{1/4%cup}, and half the cilantro. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Divide
between plates and sprinkle with @pepitas{1%ounce} and remaining cilantro.